    E -
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.Set<E>, java.util.SortedSet<E>, OperatingSet<E>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    SortedTreeModel.TNode

    public class SortedArraySet<E>
extends ArraySet<E>
implements java.util.SortedSet<E>
    SortedArraySet is an extension of ArraySet implementing the SortedSet interface. All elements inserted into this set must implement the Comparable interface or be accepted by a specified comparator. A sorted set has advantage when a single set is used iteratively with dominating membership requests or set operations (OperatingSet), for their execution time.

    If instances have to be serialised, any comparator supplied needs to implement the java.io.Serializable interface.

    Complexities (of the implementation of this class):
    Single item: insertion, removal and iteration cost O(n), membership O(log n) execution time, n = size(). Set operations (s1, s2) (OperatingSet) cost O(n+m) with n=|s1|, m=|s2|.

    • Method Detail

      • setComparator

        public void setComparator(java.util.Comparator<? super E> comparator)
        Sets the Comparator defining the total order on the elements of this set. A value of null sets usage of the natural ordering of the elements. If the set contains elements, it is implicitly resorted by a call of this method.

        NOTE: If this instance of SortedArraySet shall be serialised, the given comparator has to implement the java.io.Serializable interface and supply a unique long serialVersionUID.

        Parameters:
        comparator - Comparator, null for "natural ordering"

      • equals

        public boolean equals(java.lang.Object o)
        Compares the specified object with this set for equality. Returns true if and only if the specified object is also a SortedSet both sets have the same size, and all corresponding pairs of elements in the two sets are equal. (Two elements e1 and e2 are equal if (e1==null ? e2==null : e1.equals(e2)).) In other words, two sorted-sets are defined to be equal if they contain the same elements in the same order.
